<sawd:dashboardPage xmlns:sawd="com.siebel.analytics.web/dashboard/v1.1" xmlns:saw="com.siebel.analytics.web/report/v1.1" xmlVersion="200810300" isEmpty="false" duid="7phg03mhjnr17aso" xmlns:xsd="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"><sawd:dashboardColumn name="Column 1" canFreeze="false" duid="jo6a8hsjojjoes5c" frozen="false" layoutType="bestFit"><sawd:dashboardSection name="Section 3" showHeading="true" duid="190b029g0rfen5u2" showSectionTitle="true" horizontalLayout="true" layoutType="bestFit"><saw:caption><saw:text>Explanation</saw:text></saw:caption><sawd:htmlView name="HTML 0" duid="rc2v98vqds0nq1ut"><sawd:HTML fmt="html">[b]What this page is meant to illustrate:[/b][br/][br/]
In OBIEE 11g, Screen reader users are mostly covered by setting Accessibility Mode to ON. However, other users with accessibility needs may not need or use a screen reader. As a result, these users will not want to have to live with the restrictions applied with Accessibility Mode. These users can see, but need assistance in other ways.[br/][br/]
The displays shown here are a few examples of design techniques that you [u][i][b]must add[/b][/i][/u]    to your designs to make your content fully accessible, especially for users who don&#39;t need a screen reader and do not [b]want[/b] to use Accessibility Mode. [br/][br/]
Remember these 2 Accessibility Basics:[br/]
1) Deploying accessible content is possible with OBIEE, but it is [u][i][b]not[/b][/i][/u]   automatic. You as the content creator must consciously make a number of design changes to implement the accessible content features that are available in OBIEE.[br/]
2) Designing for accessibility means you need to cover [u][i][b]all[/b][/i][/u]   user communities, not just blind users. (For example, sighted users may have color discrimination issues, or need to use a keyboard instead of a mouse.)[br/]
